ce:section.ce:para:
In this work, nitrogen-doped CDs are functioned as the optical probe and Fe3+ is worked as the switching to control the fluorescence of CDs, which is capable of great quenching fluorescence of CDs. However, when ALP is present, AAP is decomposed into AA and phosphate group (Pi). Then, the produced AA is able to reduce Fe3+ to form Fe2+ 
                     [16,31] and the yielded phosphate group is able to bind Fe3+ to form stable FePO4 complex, [35] resulting in the fluorescence recovery of CDs (Scheme 1
                     ). Herein, this synergistic effect of chemical redox by AA and strong electrostatic binding with phosphate group greatly reduces the quenching capability of Fe3+ towards CDs. In previous reports, [16,31] the chemical redox of Fe3+ by AA was well elaborate. In this work, it focuses on the effect of phosphate group to furthermore confirm the synergistic effect, which finds new insights for ALP activity detection based on the decomposition of AAP.
